{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"423a331d-16d4-4171-9a92-9f63e065cc97","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n}\n```\n\n**Why switch:**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor could throw instead of `CreateUser`)\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` pinpoints the exact call and lets you assert on the exception details (message, `ParamName`, inner exception, etc.)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7876ae4d-4e53-4e7a-929c-bf99254b463e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question — no need to explore the codebase.","outputTokens":250,"requestId":"9836:13C8F3:10204E7:145A743:69FFDFCC"},"id":"58475477-7542-4e22-bd72-c68e5df2a12c","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:30:59.124Z","parentId":"3dddea43-dbe2-4cc0-818f-e8f52cf28f77"}
